$
ewcommand{\mc}{\mathcal} 
ewcommand{\set}[1]{\{#1\}} \DeclareMathOperator{\pr}{pr} 
ewcommand{\at}{ ig|} \DeclareMathOperator{\GL}{GL}$ Let $\pi:E	o N$ be a smooth vector bundle over a smooth manifold $N$ with typical fibre a $k$-dimensional vector space $\mc V$ and $f:M	o N$ be a smooth map between smooth manifolds. Is it true that the total space of the pullback bundle $\Pi:f^*E	o M$ is an embedded submanifold of $M	imes E$? (For reference, I have described the pullback construction I below). I think the above is true. It is clear that $f^*E$ has the subspace topology induced from $M	imes E$. So we only need to check that the inclusion map is a smooth immersion. When passing to charts, this is equivalent to checking that the map $(m, v)\mapsto (m, f(m), v):f^{-1}(U)	imes \mc V	o f^{-1}(U)	imes U	imes \mc V$ is an immersion, where $U$ is an open set in $N$ over which $E$ trivializes. But this is indeed an immersion. If the assertion is correct, then to check if a map $g:Q	o f^*E$ is smooth, we would just need to check if $\pr_1\circ g$ and $\pr_2\circ g$ are smooth (and this was the motivation for the question). Thanks. Pullback Bundle Construction: Let $\pi:E	o N$ be a smooth vector bundle over a smooth manifold $N$ with typical fibre a $k$-dimensional vector space $\mc V$ and $f:M	o N$ be a smooth map between smooth manifolds. Define the set $f^*E=M	imes_N E=\set{(p, x)\in M	imes E:\ f(p)=\pi(x)}$. Define $\Pi:f^*E	o M$ as the restriction of $\pr_1:M	imes E	o M$ to $M	imes_N E$. We will write $(f^*E)_p$ to denote $\Pi^{-1}(p)$ for each $p\in M$. Now for each smooth local trivialization $\phi:\pi^{-1}(U)	o U	imes \mc V$ of $E$ over $U$, define a map $\Phi:\Pi^{-1}(f^{-1}(U))	o f^{-1}(U)	imes \mc V$ as $\Phi(p, v)=(p, \pr_2\circ \phi(v))$ and note that $\Phi$ is a bijection whose restriction to $\Pi^{-1}(p)$ is a linear isomorphism from $(f^*E)_p$ to $\set{p}	imes \mc V$ for each $p\in f^{-1}(U)$. For each $q\in U$, write $\phi_q$ to mean $\pr_2\circ \phi\at_{E_q}$ and note that $\phi_q:E_q	o \mc V$ is a linear isomorphism. Let $\phi:\pi^{-1}(U)	o U	imes \mc V$ and $\psi:\pi^{-1}(V)	o V	imes \mc V$ be two overlapping smooth local trivializations of $U$ and $V$ over $V$ and $\Phi:\Pi^{-1}(f^{-1}(U))	o f^{-1}(U)	imes \mc V$ and $\Phi:\Pi^{-1}(f^{-1}(V))	o f^{-1}(V)	imes \mc V$ be the corresponding bijections. If $	au:U	imes V	o \GL(\mc V)$ is the transition function associated with $\psi\circ \phi^{-1}$, then note that $\Psi\circ \Phi^{-1}:f^{-1}(U\cap V)	imes \mc V	o f^{-1}(U\cap V)	imes \mc V$ is given by  egin{equation*} 	\Psi\circ \Phi^{-1}(p, v)=(p, 	au_{f(p)}v) \end{equation*} for all $(p, v)\in (U\cap V)	imes \mc V$. Defining $\Gamma:f^{-1}(U\cap V)	o \GL(\mc V)$ as $\Gamma=	au\circ f$ we see that %equation  egin{equation*} 	\Psi\circ\Phi^{-1}(p, v) = (p, \Gamma_p(v)) \end{equation*} for all $(p, v)\in f^{-1}(U\cap V)	imes \mc V$. It is clear that $\Gamma$ is smooth. Therefore there is a unique topology and smooth structure such that $\Pi:f^*E	o M$ is smooth vector bundle with typical fibre $\mc V$ whose smooth local trivializations are the maps $\Phi:f^{-1}(U)	o U	imes \mc V$ as defined above.

